President Obama and French President Hollande had a phone call to discuss shared security concerns, including Mali, Algeria, Libya, and Syria. They expressed support for France's leadership in addressing terrorism in Mali and discussed the need for the African-led International Support Mission to be established quickly. They also emphasized the importance of the Interim Government of Mali establishing a political roadmap for elections and restoration of democratic governance. The two leaders condemned the recent terrorist act in Algeria and expressed their commitment to countering terrorism in North Africa. They also discussed the humanitarian crisis in Syria and their commitment to assisting the Syrian people in achieving a political transition.